":"Gwynedd, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tredegar, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Tredegar, Monmouthshire, Wales","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales"},"en":{"1490–7 August 1517":"1490–7 August 1517","1490–1517":"1490–1517","1492–1553":"1492–1553","1512–1585":"1512–1585","1471–1514":"1471–1514","1474–1501":"1474–1501","1471":"1471","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","4 June 1514":"4 June 1514","4 May 1510":"4 May 1510","1514":"1514","1513":"1513","1501":"1501","1512":"1512","1553":"1553","7 August 1517":"7 August 1517","1585":"1585","1474":"1474","1517":"1517","Caernarfon, Gwynedd, Wales":"Richmond, Surrey, England","Poynings, Sussex, England":"Poynings, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Hurstmonceaux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Scrivelsby Court, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby Court, Lincolnshire, England","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Tredegar, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Tredegar, Monmouthshire, Wales","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Louth, Westmeath) and Scottish: shortened form of   McClinton  .","English: habitational name, either from Glympton in Oxfordshire, named as ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) on the Glym river’, a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright stream’, or from Glinton in Northamptonshire, early recorded as <i>Clinton</i> (named with an unrecorded Old English element akin to Middle Low German <i>glinde</i> ‘enclosure, fence’ + Old English <i>tūn</i>). The surname was taken to Ireland in or before the 16th century.","History: Charles Clinton (born 1690 in Longford, Ireland) organized a group of colonists and founded the settlement of Little Britain, Ulster County, NY, in 1731. His son George Clinton (1739–1812) was governor of NY (1777–95), and they had many prominent descendants. — An English aristocratic family called <i>Clinton</i> was founded by Geoffrey de Clinton (flourished 1130), who held lands at Glympton, Oxfordshire. He was chamberlain and treasurer to Henry I (1100–35)."],"variants":[{"name":"McClinton","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionntain</b> (Scottish), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntáin</b> (Irish) ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Fionntan</i>’, whose name has been explained as ‘the white ancient’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Clinton 8th Lord Clinton was born in 1490, in Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Clinton, was 19 and his mother, Elizabeth Morgan, was 17. He married Joan Poynings on 4 May 1510, in Poynings, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He registered for military service in 1513. In 1568, his occupation is listed as high sheriff of co. hertford in Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He died on 7 August 1517, in Richmond, Surrey, England, at the age of 27, and was buried in Caernarfonshire, Wales."},"et":{"1490–7 August 1517":"1490–7. august 1517","1490–1517":"1490–1517","1492–1553":"1492–1553","1512–1585":"1512–1585","1471–1514":"1471–1514","1474–1501":"1474–1501","1471":"1471","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","4 June 1514":"4. juuni 1514","4 May 1510":"4. mai 1510","1514":"1514","1513":"1513","1501":"1501","1512":"1512","1553":"1553","7 August 1517":"7. august 1517","1585":"1585","1474":"1474","1517":"1517"